The stack is faster and more efficient than the heap because it is limited in size. The stack is also faster because it is stored in a contiguous memory area. The heap is slower because it is not stored in a contiguous memory area.

The stack is used for storing local variables and function arguments because it is faster and more efficient. The heap is used for storing dynamically allocated variables and data because it is slower and less efficient.

## Dynamic Memory Allocation

Dynamic memory allocation is the process of allocating memory for a variable or data at runtime. The memory is allocated from the heap and is freed when it is no longer needed.

Dynamic memory allocation is useful for allocating memory for large amounts of data that is not known at compile time. For example, a program may need to allocate memory for a large array of integers.

The following example shows how to use dynamic memory allocation in C:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

