## Dynamic Memory Allocation in C++

In C++, dynamic memory allocation is done using the `new` and `delete` operators. The `new` operator allocates memory on the heap and the `delete` operator frees the memory.

The following program allocates a `person` structure on the heap and prints the name and status:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string.h>

using namespace std;

struct person {
    char name[100];
    int status;
};

int main() {
    // allocate a new person
    person *p = new person;
    // set status to 0
    p->status = 0;
    // set name to "Bob"
    strcpy(p->name, "Bob");
    // print the name and status
    cout << "Name: " << p->name << endl;
    cout << "Status: " << p->status << endl;
    // free the memory
    delete p;
    return 0;
}
```

The output of the program is:

```
